    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>School Budgets And Angry Parents</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rita Tancredi letter on April 16 article on opposition by parents to school budgets and constant tax increases</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Adding Revolt to the 3 R's'' (April 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Adding Revolt to the 3 R's'' (April 16):</p>
        <p>With the school budget vote looming, there are many residents who are contemplating voting down the budget because of frustration at the constant tax increases.</p>
        <p>People, when you vote down a budget you are voting down activities for your children. Most of the budget you vote on includes school buses, extracurricular activities and similar items. Teachers' salaries and benefits are what you should be concentrating on.</p>
        <p>It is the election of school board members that is important because they are the ones who negotiate the contracts of the employees, and that is where the majority of the funds goes. Many negotiators are pushovers, and teachers end up with salaries approaching six figures! Add on benefits, and that's where your taxes go!</p>
        <p>Be more aware of whom you elect to the school board, and make sure that they and the superintendent are tough negotiators. Until that happens, your taxes will rise and rise and rise.</p>
        <p>Rita Tancredi  Freeport</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
